Step 1: CUI Extraction from Multiple Sources
For each atomic concept (e.g., 8 candidates for "current medication"):
    cuis = cui_api(atomic_concept.text)
    for cui in cuis:
        cui.source_type = "atomic_concept"
        cui.source_id = atomic_concept.id  # e.g., "fc_001"
    add to merged pool

For each sub-nature (e.g., 5 sub-natures for "current medication"):
    cuis = cui_api(sub_nature.category_path)  
    # e.g., "Medication >> Drug Name >> Active"
    for cui in cuis:
        cui.source_type = "sub_nature"
        cui.source_id = sub_nature.id
    add to merged pool

For each intent (e.g., 2 intents):
    cuis = cui_api(intent.nature)  
    # e.g., "Medication History / Active Status Assessment"
    for cui in cuis:
        cui.source_type = "nature"
        cui.source_id = intent.id
    add to merged pool
The merged pool now contains CUIs from three different source types. A typical "current medication" query might produce 30-50 atomic-concept CUIs, 15-25 sub-nature CUIs, and 5-10 nature CUIs — roughly 50-85 CUIs total.
Step 2: Summarization on the Enriched Pool
reduced_pool = summarizer(merged_pool)
# Source tags travel with surviving CUIs
# Some abstract CUIs (from nature/sub-nature) likely become 
# cluster representatives because they sit higher in the 
# UMLS hierarchy
Step 3: Topic Formation
topics = topic_formation(reduced_pool)
# Each topic is a cluster of semantically related CUIs
# Topics inherit source tags from their constituent CUIs
A typical topic now contains a mix of source types. For example, Topic A might contain:

C0013227 (Pharmaceutical Preparations) — from nature "Medication History"
C0025598 (Metformin-related) — from atomic concept fc_002 "brand name medication"
C0020616 (Hypoglycemic Agents) — from sub-nature "Medication >> Classification >> Type"
C0086093 (Operative Procedure) — from atomic concept fc_005 "medication dose"

The topic's CUIs come from heterogeneous sources, and there's no clean way to identify which source "owns" the topic.
Step 4: Metadata Consolidation (THE BREAKING POINT)
This is where Possibility A becomes incoherent. For each topic, you'd want to look up source items and union their context retrieval. But the source types behave differently:
For Topic A with mixed sources:

For atomic-concept-derived CUIs:
    Look up the atomic concept in Nature Breakdown output
    Grab its 5 context retrieval dimensions
    These are well-defined.

For sub-nature-derived CUIs:
    Sub-natures DO NOT have their own context retrieval.
    The 5 dimensions live at the atomic concept level only.
    These CUIs have NO context retrieval to contribute.

For nature-derived CUIs:
    Nature strings are even higher up.
    They have NO context retrieval.
You're left with two bad options:
Option A1 — Skip nature/sub-nature CUIs in metadata consolidation:
The topic's metadata is built only from atomic-concept-derived CUIs in the topic. But the topic exists partly because of nature/sub-nature CUIs that pulled it together — its semantic shape doesn't match its metadata. The Stage 0 scoping based on this partial metadata might miss what the user actually wanted.
Option A2 — Fabricate context retrieval for orphan CUIs:
Inherit context retrieval from sibling atomic-concept CUIs in the same topic. If no atomic-concept CUIs are in the topic, invent a default. This is fabricated metadata that doesn't trace back to anything Nature Breakdown actually produced.
Step 5: Send Enriched Topics to Adapter
For each topic, attach (incoherently) consolidated metadata:
    Topic.consolidated_document_types = union from atomic-concept 
        sources only (or fabricated if none)
    Topic.consolidated_author_roles = same problem
    Topic.consolidated_temporal_signals = same problem
    Topic.consolidated_content_signals = same problem
    Topic.consolidated_clinical_setting = same problem
    Topic.sub_nature_paths = whichever sub-natures any 
        contributing CUI traces back to (could be many)
    Topic.intent_ids = whichever intents any contributing 
        CUI traces back to (could be multiple)
What Goes Wrong

Orphan CUIs: Nature-derived and sub-nature-derived CUIs have no context retrieval. The enrichment is partial or fabricated.
Precision dilution: Abstract CUIs from nature and sub-nature ("medication," "clinical assessment") match almost any clinical record and dominate topic clusters.
Topic spanning: Abstract CUIs glue together topics that should stay clinically distinct, causing topics to span sub-natures and intents.
Stage 0 scoping diluted: Consolidated document_types becomes broad and incoherent.
Contradicts Nature Breakdown's design: Nature and sub-nature paths are organizational labels, not CUI-ready text. The Nature Breakdown prompt explicitly engineers atomic concepts to be CUI-resolvable; nature and sub-nature paths are not given this treatment.

Verdict: Rejected. The enrichment mechanics break because nature and sub-nature don't carry context retrieval. The metadata consolidation is incoherent.
